---
import Header from "../../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import { siteConfig } from "../../config";
import "../../styles/global.css";

const projectName = "ABB Lifter Force Analysis Study";
const projectTagline =
  "Two industrial scissor lifts, taken from geometry to load path to a punch list of fixes.";
const projectSummary =
  "A statics study of two industrial scissor lifts analyzed during my robotics internship, checking each against a 1000 kg payload target across its real travel envelope and stating what it needs to carry that load safely.";

const imgBase = "/images/projects/abb-lifter";
const accent = siteConfig.accentColor;
const btn =
  "inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-5 py-3 rounded-xl font-semibold text-white";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <title>{projectName} | {siteConfig.name}</title>
    <meta name="description" content={projectSummary} />
  </head>

  <body class="bg-background text-foreground">
    <Header />

    <main class="pt-24 pb-16">
      <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 space-y-10">
        {/* Header */}
        <header class="space-y-3">
          <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.25em]" style={`color:${accent}`}>Project</p>
          <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-100">{projectName}</h1>
          <p class="text-base sm:text-lg text-gray-400">{projectTagline}</p>
          <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-gray-400">{projectSummary}</p>
        </header>

        {/* Cover */}
        <section class="space-y-3">
          <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/60 p-4">
            <img
              src={`${imgBase}/fig18-stroke-hold.png`}
              alt="Shaft lifter travel envelope at true scale, showing closed, working, and top poses"
              class="w-full h-auto rounded-xl bg-white"
              loading="eager"
            />
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
              The travel envelope at true scale. A scissor lift is a force multiplier that gets worse as it
              closes, so the lowest angle governs every structural check.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        {/* Two subpage buttons */}
        <section class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
          <a href="/projects/abb-lifter-shaft" class={btn} style={`background-color:${accent}`}>
            Shaft Lifter Study →
          </a>
          <a href="/projects/abb-lifter-case" class={btn} style={`background-color:${accent}`}>
            Case Lifter Study →
          </a>
        </section>

        {/* Validation */}
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-emerald-900/40 bg-emerald-950/20 px-4 py-3">
          <p class="text-sm text-emerald-200/80 leading-relaxed">
            The numbers were independently re-derived by two adversarial AI verification passes, one for statics
            and geometry and one for materials and failure theory, and reviewed by K. The validation covers the
            arithmetic and statics.
          </p>
        </div>

        {/* Objective */}
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-100">Objective</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            I was asked to structurally validate two industrial scissor lifts against a 1000 kg payload
            requirement (plus a roughly 150 to 165 kg platform, with a safety factor of 1.5 applied to the
            working weight), throughout each machine's real travel, and to identify what each needs to carry
            that load safely. Actuation sizing was out of scope: sourcing a cylinder that meets the demand is the
            actuation vendor's problem, and the analysis states the force demand where the vendor needs it.
            Actuation-side components, including the cylinder cross member on the shaft lifter, are the actuation
            vendor's scope and were not analyzed.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* Measured basis */}
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-100">Measured basis</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            Every dimension was taken from the supplied CAD assemblies through section cuts and dimension
            callouts. The material grade could not be confirmed, so all stresses assume mild steel at a yield of
            250 MPa and a shear yield of 145 MPa. The analysis is static, hand-derived, and cross-checked with a
            parametric script.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* The mechanics */}
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-100">The mechanics: multiplier versus angle</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            A scissor lift near its closed position multiplies force brutally. The horizontal actuator force is
            the lifted weight divided by the tangent of the arm angle, and every joint load scales the same way,
            with one over the tangent. So the lowest angle in the travel governs every structural check. The
            shaft lifter multiplies 5.78x at its 9.82 degree working pose and 16.1x at its 3.56 degree bottom of
            stroke. The case lifter starts from a worse 5.23 degree floor, a 10.92x multiplier, which its joints
            absorb but its actuation must respect.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* Callout: top hinge */}
        <section class="space-y-3">
          <div class="rounded-2xl border p-6 space-y-3" style="background-color:#0f141c; border-color:#1c2330;">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-100">Why the top hinge carries no horizontal force</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
              It is the question every engineer asks first when they see one hinge design used top and bottom.
              Treat the platform as a free body. Its only horizontal connections are the top hinge and the top
              roller, and a frictionless roller transmits no horizontal force, so horizontal equilibrium of the
              platform forces the top hinge's horizontal reaction to zero. The entire multiplied actuation force
              (93.6 kN per side on the case lifter, 48.9 kN per side on the shaft lifter) stays in the bottom
              half of the machine and circulates between the arms, the base pins, and the cylinder. The top
              hinge only carries its small vertical share. Real rollers are not perfectly frictionless, so roller
              friction adds an estimated 10 to 20 percent, which is why the top hinge is small rather than exactly
              zero.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        {/* Headline results: shaft */}
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-100">Headline result: shaft lifter</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            Capacity is pin-governed. At and above the working pose the joints check out with margin (end pins at
            67 percent of allowable, center pins at 37 percent). From the machine's lowest reachable point (3.56
            degrees, the 16.1x multiplier) the rated payload is 474 kg at the 1.5 safety factor, or 786 kg loaded
            to the shear allowable with no safety factor. The 1000 kg target therefore exists only at or above the
            working pose, and it remains contingent on closing the open items in the shaft study.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            Two real deficiencies stand out as delivered. The sliding-end linear bearings run 106 to 132 percent
            of their static rating at design load, the machine's first structural failure under full load, with
            brinelling as the expected mode. The descent stop is non-functional, sitting 287 mm below the
            reachable bottom, so it can never engage and the low-angle overstress zone is left unguarded. Full
            calculations, the open-items punch list, and a note on the limits of the arm bending model are in the
            shaft study.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* Headline results: case */}
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-100">Headline result: case lifter</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            Every structural check passes across the entire travel envelope. This machine has real 25 mm
            double-shear axles with retention (66 percent of allowable), a 30 mm center bushing (46 percent in
            double shear, and still inside allowable at 91 percent even read as single shear), solid 25 by 70 mm
            arms (68 percent of yield), and ball-bearing rollers at 38 percent of rating. Its modeled pose is
            genuinely the bottom of stroke, so there is no hidden low-angle trap. The one open risk is
            behavioral: two independent cylinders with no synchronization, which can rack the platform under
            uneven extension. The single recommendation is a flow divider, a rephasing circuit, or a mechanical
            tie between sides.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* Recommendations */}
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-100">Recommendations</h2>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-300">
            <li><span class="font-medium">Shaft:</span> add a third linear bearing block per sliding end or fit higher-rated carriages; install a descent stop that engages at or above the working pose; specify and positively retain the arm-end axles; close the arm beam-column check now that the section is measured; confirm material certificates.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium">Case:</span> add cylinder synchronization; verify the center pivot's double-shear construction next time the joint is opened; confirm material certificates.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        {/* Bottom buttons */}
        <section class="space-y-3 pt-2">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Read the full analysis for each machine:</p>
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
            <a href="/projects/abb-lifter-shaft" class={btn} style={`background-color:${accent}`}>
              Shaft Lifter Study →
            </a>
            <a href="/projects/abb-lifter-case" class={btn} style={`background-color:${accent}`}>
              Case Lifter Study →
            </a>
          </div>
        </section>

        {/* Back link */}
        <div class="pt-4">
          <a href="/projects" class="text-sm underline-offset-2 hover:underline" style={`color:${accent}`}>
            ← Back to all projects
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
